[vc_row full_width=&quot;&quot; parallax=&quot;&quot; parallax_image=&quot;&quot; lvca_dark_bg=&quot;&quot;][vc_column width=&quot;1/1&quot;][lvca_team style=&quot;style2&quot; per_line=&quot;1&quot;][lvca_team_member member_name=&quot;Bruce Curran&quot; member_image=&quot;272832&quot; member_position=&quot;Independent Investment Expert&quot; member_details=&quot;Bruce Curran has been advising companies and individuals in Asia about international fundinvestment for over 30 years. He was a Director of the Swire Group in Hong Kong and has written numerous financial articles for Merrill Lynch, The Security Bank, and The Billionaire Magazine, and he was also a regular columnist for the Business World newspaper as well as Time magazine. Now an Independent Financial Adviser, he is here to share his views, suggestions and recommendations with those curious about investment in this vast jungle of opportunities.&quot;][/lvca_team][vc_separator color=&quot;grey&quot; align=&quot;align_center&quot;][vc_column_text]&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;Gold is a classic asset class that is well worth considering for investing 5% of an overall portfolio.

&lt;strong&gt;Fund Facts&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Fund Name: Aliquot Gold Bullion Inc.&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Investment Manager: Castlestone Management Inc.&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Custodian: Barclays Capital&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Domicile: British Virgin Islands&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Auditors: Deloitte Accountants&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Regulator: British Virgin Islands Financial Services Commission&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;The Fund:&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Aims to provide unleveraged, direct exposure to physical gold bullion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;No equity exposure and no corporate risk, the Fund only holds the physical metal&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Daily liquidity&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Available in USD, EUR and GBP&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Minimum Investment 10,000 in all 3 currencies&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Why invest in Gold Bullion?&lt;/strong&gt;

Gold is a ‘safe-haven’ asset in times of economic and geopolitical uncertainty, and in price sensitive and reactionary markets. The production cost for an ounce of gold is estimated to be in the $1200 range. Currently the price is well above this and there is a strong possibility of further price rises.  If HSBC are to be believed, they are claiming the price could rise to $1500.

&amp;nbsp;

There is a strong correlation between gold prices and the increase in money supply. Gold can be the hedge against inflation, against the devaluation of money and also against low or negative interest rates. It is often used as a hedge against Central Bank intervention.

&amp;nbsp;

The rising demand from emerging market countries, Central Banks and other investment houses, is expected to continue to keep gold prices buoyant.

Gold is uncorrelated to other asset classes, provides diversification and broadens the frontier of a diversified portfolio.

&amp;nbsp;

&lt;strong&gt;Gold Hitting New Highs.&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ft.com/topics/themes/Gold&quot;&gt;Gold&lt;/a&gt; is currently a very telling, positive and compelling story. Sentiment remains strong with Gold pricing hitting a 15-month high by the end of April, with the previous week showing a gain of 4.7%, the highest percentage move since early February.

&amp;nbsp;

The biggest shift in sentiment has been among market professionals. Out of 36 market experts contacted, 21 responded, of which 15 professionals, or 71%, said they are ‘bullish’ on gold; at the same time five professionals, or 29%, said they are bearish. No analyst was neutral on the market.  Market participants include bullion dealers, investment banks, futures traders and technical-chart analysts.

&amp;nbsp;

&lt;strong&gt;Market Analysts Bullish on Gold.&lt;/strong&gt;

&amp;nbsp;

According to comments from market participants, many are bullish on gold as the U.S. dollar is expected to push lower with the Federal Reserve expected to keep interest rates static.

“With the dollar falling, we are seeing a manic move into gold by those who are short or on the sidelines,” said Adrian Day, President of Adrian Day Asset Management.

Colin Ciesznski, senior market strategist at CMC Markets, said that, along with a weaker U.S. dollar as other currencies catch up due to shifting global monetary policies, the technical picture for gold has significantly improved. “This week’s rally called off a head-and-shoulders top that had been forming, a bullish sign,” he said.

Even the bearish analysts remain optimistic that gold will continue to hold most of its recent gains. Richard Baker, editor of the Eureka Miner newsletter, said that he could see prices fall back and take a breather next week following the latest rally.

After four years of sharp falls, a sudden revival has been taking place in the Gold market. In the first three months of 2016 the price of the yellow metal soared by 20% - its best quarterly performance since the financial crisis erupted in the final three months of 2008.

&amp;nbsp;

The gold price, around $1,260 an ounce, is well below its record peak of almost $1,900 achieved in July 2011, at the height of the European sovereign debt crisis.

&amp;nbsp;

For investors who have missed out on the rally so far, the big question is: has gold turned a corner, suggesting that it will continue to rise, or will it crash back down to earth?

&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;Who has been buying gold?&lt;/strong&gt;

&amp;nbsp;

Central banks are among the buyers, but, more importantly, according to Charles Morris, who edits the AtlasPulse Report gold newsletter, there has been a change in sentiment from investors, private as well as institutional.

“Changes in investor interest explain 80% of the move in the gold price.”

&amp;nbsp;

&lt;strong&gt;The time to buy is now!&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;

Gold is the precious metal currently hitting the headlines, and will always have a place in a well-diversified personal portfolio.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=&quot;1/1&quot;][vc_column_text]
